f the processes by which an authoritative text is established.The Writings of James Fenimore CooperThe distinguished Cooper scholar James Franklin Beard (1919–1989) began organizing the Writings of James Fenimore Cooper in the late 1960s, as his work on publishing the monumental Letters and Journals of James Fenimore Cooper came to fulfillment. Beard's intention was to provide readers with sound scholarly editions of Cooper's major works, based wherever possible on authorial manuscripts. To date, the Writings of James Fenimore Cooper has made available texts of many of Cooper's best-known novels, as well as some of his most important works of political and social commentary.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturey19th century. 0aSea stories, American. 0aSeafaring life. 4aGeneral Interest : Fiction. 4aHistory : American History. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aPhilbrick, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhilbrick, Marianne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPhilbrick, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhilbrick, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848523240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438485232423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438485232/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles